1
00:00:02,127 --> 00:00:04,647
NARRATOR: Previously on
Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles:

2
00:00:04,797 --> 00:00:07,840
- You've got a nuclear sub?
- Seawolf sub.

3
00:00:08,008 --> 00:00:10,927
The Jimmy Carter. We got a scrubbed
Trip-8 for a captain.

4
00:00:11,095 --> 00:00:13,638
Damn it, Cameron.
You're supposed to burn the endos.

5
00:00:13,806 --> 00:00:15,306
What's happening with you?

6
00:00:15,474 --> 00:00:17,558
CAMERON:
I've planted an explosive in my skull.

7
00:00:17,726 --> 00:00:21,312
It's a small amount, but enough.
RILEY: I saw the metal. She knows I saw it.

8
00:00:21,480 --> 00:00:24,607
- Master fear. Remember the mission.
- I can't go back there.

9
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:28,945
You are here to keep John Connor
away from her.

10
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:32,573
- I can get her to tell me the truth.
- Stay away.

11
00:00:32,741 --> 00:00:36,035
Cameron's supposed to kill me.
You knew that was the only thing...

12
00:00:36,203 --> 00:00:38,037
...that would turn John against her.

13
00:00:38,205 --> 00:00:41,916
I rescued you from hell,
and I took you to paradise.

14
00:00:42,084 --> 00:00:43,292
[GRUNTING]

15
00:00:43,460 --> 00:00:44,627
[GUNSHOT]

16
00:01:33,802 --> 00:01:36,262
You don't need to be so dramatic.
It's a milk run.

17
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:39,599
A milk run across 8000 miles
of metal-infested ocean.

18
00:01:39,767 --> 00:01:41,809
If you're gonna be like this
every time...

19
00:01:41,977 --> 00:01:44,896
Listen. Jesse,
I'm going on a mission too.

20
00:01:45,063 --> 00:01:48,775
- Oh, I see. One of those missions.
- No.

21
00:01:49,318 --> 00:01:50,359
It's something else.

22
00:01:51,820 --> 00:01:54,572
- It's different.
- Different?

23
00:01:54,740 --> 00:01:55,782
How's it different?

24
00:01:55,949 --> 00:01:59,076
- What does "different" mean?
- "Different" means different.

25
00:02:00,788 --> 00:02:02,038
Just listen to me.

26
00:02:03,332 --> 00:02:07,502
You're stuck in a can under the ocean
with one of those things.

27
00:02:08,253 --> 00:02:10,421
Don't worry about Queeg.
He's a good bloke.

28
00:02:10,589 --> 00:02:12,298
He's not a bloke.

29
00:02:13,217 --> 00:02:15,885
Jesse, he's not on our side.
Don't ever think that.

30
00:02:18,597 --> 00:02:20,598
Aim for the chip.

31
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:25,603
Aim for the chip, they don't get up.

32
00:02:33,904 --> 00:02:35,404
I love you too.

33
00:02:38,784 --> 00:02:40,034
Derek.

34
00:02:43,288 --> 00:02:44,956
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

35
00:02:46,542 --> 00:02:48,668
It means, "I'll see you later."

36
00:02:50,879 --> 00:02:52,505
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

37
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:10,189
What are you doing?

38
00:03:10,732 --> 00:03:12,358
Moving.

39
00:03:13,485 --> 00:03:16,654
Yeah, well,
seems about the right time for that.

40
00:03:18,073 --> 00:03:20,533
Get your stuff sorted.

41
00:03:20,951 --> 00:03:24,745
I'm nearly done with the living room.
I'm gonna start on the garage.

42
00:03:25,163 --> 00:03:28,499
Uh... Well, hey, why don't you let me
take the garage?

43
00:03:29,126 --> 00:03:31,794
I got a lot of memory cards
and flash drives out there.

44
00:03:31,962 --> 00:03:36,549
I don't want to save our Dakara records
and torch my copy of "Space Invaders."

45
00:03:37,676 --> 00:03:39,135
It's all yours.

46
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:42,013
Thanks.

47
00:03:55,319 --> 00:03:56,360
[SIGHS]

48
00:03:56,528 --> 00:03:59,238
Great, it looks like
a robot serial killer lives here.

49
00:03:59,406 --> 00:04:00,740
Well, I guess one does.

50
00:04:01,700 --> 00:04:04,535
- I'm doing inventory.
- Well, don't do it here.

51
00:04:04,703 --> 00:04:08,372
We need to clear all this stuff out
before Mom comes in and finds it.

52
00:04:10,584 --> 00:04:14,128
Dig a hole out back,
down below the retaining wall.

53
00:04:14,296 --> 00:04:16,756
I'll bury the parts
and come back for them later.

54
00:04:16,924 --> 00:04:19,300
We have to find a place to burn them.

55
00:04:20,177 --> 00:04:22,511
And we will burn them.

56
00:04:22,971 --> 00:04:24,972
[MUSIC PLAYING]

57
00:04:25,140 --> 00:04:27,141
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

58
00:04:43,367 --> 00:04:45,076
What you drinking?

59
00:04:45,243 --> 00:04:46,619
I don't know.

60
00:04:47,162 --> 00:04:49,163
You don't know what you're drinking?

61
00:04:50,248 --> 00:04:52,625
There's booze in it,
some sugary crap...

62
00:04:52,793 --> 00:04:55,753
...to cut the hell out
of the burning taste, and some ice.

63
00:04:57,339 --> 00:04:59,131
Of course, this one's pretty much empty.

64
00:05:01,468 --> 00:05:04,553
Could you get her another one
of whatever she's drinking?

65
00:05:04,721 --> 00:05:07,765
- If you don't know, how do you order it?
- Just like you did.

66
00:05:07,933 --> 00:05:10,810
But it's gotta start somewhere, right?
You can't sit down...

67
00:05:10,978 --> 00:05:12,937
...and ask for that right off.

68
00:05:15,273 --> 00:05:16,607
What happened to your face?

69
00:05:16,775 --> 00:05:19,944
You ask a lot of questions
for a guy who wants to get in my pants.

70
00:05:20,112 --> 00:05:22,238
- Do I?
- Yeah, see? There's another one.

71
00:05:24,116 --> 00:05:25,700
That's a nice costume.

72
00:05:25,867 --> 00:05:28,828
You thinking about a career
in the military?

73
00:05:29,621 --> 00:05:32,957
Actually, I fly P-3s. For the Navy.

74
00:05:33,208 --> 00:05:37,753
- Oh. Brown Shoe.
- Guilty as charged. You?

75
00:05:37,921 --> 00:05:40,548
- Submarine. Bubblehead.
- Oh, bubble head.

76
00:05:41,216 --> 00:05:44,301
- They let women on subs in Australia?
- Yeah.

77
00:05:44,469 --> 00:05:46,429
Reprogrammed killer robots too.

78
00:05:46,596 --> 00:05:48,597
[CHUCKLES]

79
00:05:49,641 --> 00:05:51,892
Yeah, we don't discriminate.

80
00:05:52,060 --> 00:05:54,103
Well, there's a coincidence.

81
00:05:54,563 --> 00:05:56,856
I hunt subs. You drive subs.

82
00:05:57,482 --> 00:05:59,692
Sort of like the wolf
and the sheepdog.

83
00:05:59,860 --> 00:06:02,319
Not that I'm comparing you to a dog
or anything.

84
00:06:04,197 --> 00:06:07,074
It's a good point.
In fact, I just remembered something.

85
00:06:07,242 --> 00:06:09,577
- What's that?
- Sheepdogs hate wolves.

86
00:06:12,289 --> 00:06:13,581
And I hate Brown Shoes.

87
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:23,799
I can't believe you guys
are just up and moving like this.

88
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:27,636
You could let me throw a party.
You know, you never did come to dinner.

89
00:06:27,804 --> 00:06:28,929
Tape?

90
00:06:29,097 --> 00:06:31,807
It's okay. It's not like you're moving
to Mars, right?

91
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:34,894
I mean,
we can still totally keep in touch.

92
00:06:35,062 --> 00:06:37,772
- Absolutely.
- Oh, here, let me help you with that.

93
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:39,315
No, no, I'm good. Sit down.

94
00:06:39,483 --> 00:06:42,109
You know, I'm fine.
People say it takes a while...

95
00:06:42,277 --> 00:06:45,905
...to get back to fighting trim,
but I snapped back like a rubber band.

96
00:06:46,073 --> 00:06:49,575
- You know, mostly like a rubber band.
- You look great.

97
00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:52,787
I'm thinking if I can breast-feed him
till he's 5...

98
00:06:52,954 --> 00:06:55,998
...maybe I can trick my body
into letting me keep these boobs.

99
00:06:57,292 --> 00:06:59,960
Kidding. Sort of.

100
00:07:00,128 --> 00:07:02,880
- And who's got the baby?
- Trevor.

101
00:07:04,716 --> 00:07:10,346
He's not back. He's just visiting.
He said he needed some daddy time.

102
00:07:10,722 --> 00:07:14,141
I don't blame him.
Not after the call they got last night.

103
00:07:17,020 --> 00:07:22,942
They found a girl in the river,
shot through the chest.

104
00:07:23,110 --> 00:07:27,071
Trevor said that it looked
like she'd been executed.

105
00:07:27,405 --> 00:07:28,823
That's terrible.

106
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:30,533
Pretty little blond thing.

107
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:34,161
I mean, probably moved here from Iowa
or something to be an actress...

108
00:07:34,329 --> 00:07:36,455
...fell in with the wrong people.

109
00:07:36,623 --> 00:07:38,541
Dreams die hard.

110
00:07:38,708 --> 00:07:40,543
Trevor said all they have to go on...

111
00:07:40,710 --> 00:07:42,878
...are some scars
from an attempted suicide...

112
00:07:43,046 --> 00:07:46,298
...and a tattoo on her wrist.

113
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:48,134
You know, a pretty little star.

114
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:50,719
Right here.

115
00:07:59,396 --> 00:08:00,437
Your mother's coming.

116
00:08:01,815 --> 00:08:03,691
All right, quick, hide this stuff.

117
00:08:17,831 --> 00:08:19,248
I need to talk to John.

118
00:08:22,210 --> 00:08:23,878
Alone.

119
00:08:40,145 --> 00:08:42,146
[BIRD COOING]

120
00:08:50,405 --> 00:08:51,906
Goodbye, bird.

121
00:08:52,073 --> 00:08:54,700
There's a 51 percent chance
I wouldn't have killed you.

122
00:08:54,868 --> 00:08:56,869
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

123
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:21,602
- Cameron...
- I know.

124
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:23,729
I heard you.

125
00:09:24,981 --> 00:09:26,815
Riley's dead.

126
00:09:39,329 --> 00:09:40,871
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

127
00:09:58,473 --> 00:10:00,182
Was it you?

128
00:10:01,893 --> 00:10:03,769
Did you kill her?

129
00:10:05,897 --> 00:10:07,856
What if I did?

130
00:10:10,026 --> 00:10:12,486
Don't play games with me.

131
00:10:13,154 --> 00:10:14,989
I need the truth.

132
00:10:15,156 --> 00:10:17,199
I didn't kill her.

133
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:22,037
- I wanna believe you.
- Believe me.

134
00:10:22,205 --> 00:10:24,540
Sometimes you lie to me.

135
00:10:26,293 --> 00:10:27,960
Yes.

136
00:10:28,545 --> 00:10:31,213
I do, but I'm not lying now.

137
00:10:32,465 --> 00:10:34,425
I am sorry.

138
00:10:38,221 --> 00:10:40,014
You're sorry?

139
00:10:41,182 --> 00:10:42,391
For what?

140
00:10:43,143 --> 00:10:45,060
For your loss.

141
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:50,316
I really wish I could believe that too.

142
00:11:03,455 --> 00:11:05,748
So are you gonna say anything?

143
00:11:08,501 --> 00:11:10,169
Jesse?

144
00:11:10,545 --> 00:11:13,255
- Thanks.
- Thanks.

145
00:11:13,465 --> 00:11:16,675
For bailing me out. Thanks.

146
00:11:16,843 --> 00:11:18,677
I know you don't like police stations.

147
00:11:18,845 --> 00:11:21,096
- Maybe that's because I'm a fugitive.
- I know.

148
00:11:22,724 --> 00:11:25,059
- So thanks.
- What happened?

149
00:11:28,855 --> 00:11:30,773
I told you, I got in a fight.

150
00:11:31,733 --> 00:11:35,110
With four Naval aviators.

151
00:11:35,278 --> 00:11:38,030
Really just three.
One of them went down pretty quick.

152
00:11:38,990 --> 00:11:40,866
What's going on?

153
00:11:43,787 --> 00:11:45,454
Nothing.

154
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:47,581
I don't believe you.

155
00:11:47,749 --> 00:11:50,125
I need to know
what the hell's going on.

156
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:53,253
I told you, nothing.

157
00:11:55,715 --> 00:11:56,757
[SIGHS]

158
00:12:08,770 --> 00:12:12,523
- We across the line yet?
- Not yet. Give it a tick.

159
00:12:13,525 --> 00:12:15,651
Zero degrees north,
heading south-southwest...

160
00:12:15,819 --> 00:12:17,111
...over the equator.

161
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,321
Now we've crossed the line.

162
00:12:19,489 --> 00:12:21,490
[CHEERING]

163
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:24,451
- Whoo, whoo!
- Whoo!

164
00:12:25,495 --> 00:12:27,746
One nice thing
about metal driving the boat:

165
00:12:27,914 --> 00:12:29,331
A schedule's a schedule.

166
00:12:30,333 --> 00:12:32,167
One nice thing.

167
00:12:32,335 --> 00:12:34,294
- That mean we're done?
- Quiet, you.

168
00:12:36,047 --> 00:12:37,297
Proclamation.

169
00:12:43,179 --> 00:12:46,014
"Know ye that Sonarman Second Class
Christopher Garvin...

170
00:12:46,182 --> 00:12:49,101
...on the 13th day
of September, 2027...

171
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:51,854
...aboard USS Jimmy Carter,
appeared at the equator...

172
00:12:52,021 --> 00:12:56,358
...at latitude zero, longitude 180,
entering into our royal domain...

173
00:12:56,526 --> 00:12:59,695
...and having been found worthy
by my royal staff, was initiated...

174
00:12:59,863 --> 00:13:02,865
...into the Solemn Mysteries
of the Ancient Order of the Deep.

175
00:13:03,032 --> 00:13:07,828
I command my subjects to honor him
as one of our trusty shell backs."

176
00:13:08,621 --> 00:13:10,080
Now rise, shell back.

177
00:13:12,417 --> 00:13:14,001
[CHUCKLING]

178
00:13:16,838 --> 00:13:18,881
- Never gets old, does it?
- Never.

179
00:13:19,048 --> 00:13:20,382
[RUMBLING]

180
00:13:22,218 --> 00:13:24,052
Depth charge.

181
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:29,808
General quarters. Go. Go!

182
00:13:29,976 --> 00:13:31,393
[ALARM BUZZING]

183
00:13:38,776 --> 00:13:40,444
SAVANNAH:
Boo!

184
00:13:41,863 --> 00:13:45,032
- Come and play hide-and-seek, Mommy.
- I'm working.

185
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,742
But you promised.

186
00:13:48,411 --> 00:13:52,080
Patience is a virtue, Savannah.
To tolerate delay.

187
00:13:52,248 --> 00:13:54,750
It implies self-control
and forbearance...

188
00:13:54,918 --> 00:13:57,753
...as opposed to wanting
what we want when we want it.

189
00:13:57,921 --> 00:13:59,505
Something to think about.

190
00:14:16,439 --> 00:14:18,065
[DOOR BUZZES]

191
00:14:33,122 --> 00:14:35,040
["THREE BLIND MICE"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

192
00:14:35,208 --> 00:14:37,042
[GIGGLES]

193
00:14:45,969 --> 00:14:47,344
[LAUGHING]

194
00:15:26,467 --> 00:15:29,011
Would you like to play hide-and-seek?

195
00:15:46,029 --> 00:15:49,031
Mr. Ellison. My daughter, Savannah...

196
00:15:50,199 --> 00:15:52,534
...she's missing.

197
00:15:52,702 --> 00:15:55,662
She's in the building, Mr. Ellison.
We just have to find her.

198
00:15:56,581 --> 00:15:58,749
- It's 23 stories.
- Yes.

199
00:15:58,958 --> 00:16:02,085
And there's someone who knows
what's going on on all of them.

200
00:16:08,051 --> 00:16:11,094
WEAVER: John Henry, we're looking
for my daughter, Savannah.

201
00:16:11,262 --> 00:16:13,972
- Have you seen her today?
- Yes, I have.

202
00:16:14,515 --> 00:16:17,267
- She wanted to play a game.
- Where is she now?

203
00:16:17,477 --> 00:16:19,061
She's hiding.

204
00:16:19,562 --> 00:16:23,065
- Tell us where she's hiding.
- That's not how the game works.

205
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:25,359
How does the game work?

206
00:16:25,526 --> 00:16:28,904
Hide-and-seek.
There are many variations.

207
00:16:29,072 --> 00:16:30,864
The one we're playing...

208
00:16:31,032 --> 00:16:33,950
...you guess what I'm thinking,
I give you a clue.

209
00:16:34,118 --> 00:16:37,245
Listen to me, John Henry.
You're gonna tell me where Savannah is.

210
00:16:37,413 --> 00:16:38,872
And you're gonna tell me now.

211
00:16:39,207 --> 00:16:42,042
I'm thinking of a country.

212
00:16:42,585 --> 00:16:44,378
Come again?

213
00:16:45,505 --> 00:16:47,422
Let's play the game.

214
00:16:48,591 --> 00:16:51,593
This is ridiculous.
I'm not gonna bargain with a computer.

215
00:16:51,761 --> 00:16:54,262
If I'm not mistaken, Mr. Ellison...

216
00:16:54,430 --> 00:16:55,889
...we've got no choice.

217
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:03,563
You hit him in the mouth, didn't you?

218
00:17:04,524 --> 00:17:06,983
Never aim for the mouth.

219
00:17:07,151 --> 00:17:10,028
- What's that?
- Antibiotic.

220
00:17:11,781 --> 00:17:13,990
You know, one time
when Kyle and I were kids...

221
00:17:14,158 --> 00:17:20,163
...we, uh, saw two tunnel trolls go at it
over a can of stewed tomatoes.

222
00:17:20,331 --> 00:17:23,542
The loser got three teeth knocked out,
and the winner...

223
00:17:24,293 --> 00:17:26,795
...got a blood infection
from his split knuckles...

224
00:17:26,963 --> 00:17:29,297
...and died a week later.

225
00:17:29,465 --> 00:17:31,299
The human mouth is filthy.

226
00:17:31,467 --> 00:17:32,634
[PHONE RINGING]

227
00:17:32,802 --> 00:17:34,469
You got that?

228
00:17:40,685 --> 00:17:42,144
Yeah.

229
00:17:44,605 --> 00:17:45,814
What?

230
00:17:50,570 --> 00:17:51,653
Damn.

231
00:17:56,325 --> 00:17:58,160
John okay?

232
00:17:58,995 --> 00:18:00,620
All right.

233
00:18:01,205 --> 00:18:03,957
Hold tight. I'm on my way.

234
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:09,004
[SIGHS]

235
00:18:11,174 --> 00:18:12,799
John's girlfriend is dead.

236
00:18:13,259 --> 00:18:14,843
Oh.

237
00:18:15,011 --> 00:18:16,887
A cyborg did it.

238
00:18:18,681 --> 00:18:21,558
- You know that for sure?
- Who else could it be?

239
00:18:21,726 --> 00:18:22,851
What are you gonna do?

240
00:18:23,019 --> 00:18:25,353
- About the metal?
- What are you gonna do?

241
00:18:26,230 --> 00:18:28,023
Because you can't kill her, Derek.

242
00:18:28,608 --> 00:18:31,860
- What?
- That's not something you can do.

243
00:18:32,028 --> 00:18:34,529
He has to make that decision
on his own.

244
00:18:40,536 --> 00:18:43,163
You've really thought this through.

245
00:18:45,708 --> 00:18:47,167
No.

246
00:18:48,920 --> 00:18:50,921
But I think about it.

247
00:18:51,756 --> 00:18:53,173
Just like you do.

248
00:19:00,139 --> 00:19:03,934
More depth charges.
Shook us up a bit, but no damage.

249
00:19:04,143 --> 00:19:06,937
They want us to make a mistake,
reveal our position.

250
00:19:07,146 --> 00:19:09,439
A lot of metal in the water, captain.

251
00:19:09,649 --> 00:19:12,067
Barrage. Getting closer.

252
00:19:12,235 --> 00:19:15,111
- ASW bots. How many?
- Travel in packs. No way to tell.

253
00:19:15,279 --> 00:19:16,863
Mr. Garvin?

254
00:19:17,406 --> 00:19:19,032
[BEEPING]

255
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:20,700
Garvin.

256
00:19:20,868 --> 00:19:22,911
Not ASW bots.

257
00:19:28,084 --> 00:19:31,086
Oh, man, oh, man. Kraken.

258
00:19:31,254 --> 00:19:32,963
- We've got a kraken.
- You sure?

259
00:19:33,172 --> 00:19:34,422
Bet my life on it.

260
00:19:35,466 --> 00:19:38,885
- Feed the sonar picture to Tactical.
- Aye, ma'am.

261
00:19:43,307 --> 00:19:46,935
You're a big fellow, aren't you?
And you're very far from home.

262
00:19:50,773 --> 00:19:52,107
That can't be right.

263
00:19:53,276 --> 00:19:54,943
- Where are we?
- Chief of the boat...

264
00:19:55,111 --> 00:19:57,070
...status of our torpedo stock?

265
00:19:57,488 --> 00:20:00,282
Two, maybe three
I'd consider worth using in a fight.

266
00:20:00,449 --> 00:20:02,617
Ready Tube 1. Hold for my order.

267
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:11,001
Queeg, we can't fight a kraken
with one torpedo. Or three.

268
00:20:11,210 --> 00:20:14,004
We need to break contact
and find a way around.

269
00:20:14,213 --> 00:20:16,631
Mr. Garvin, active sonar, please.

270
00:20:16,799 --> 00:20:18,133
One ping only.

271
00:20:21,804 --> 00:20:23,638
One ping, aye.

272
00:20:26,309 --> 00:20:27,392
[SONAR PINGS]

273
00:20:29,478 --> 00:20:32,606
Torpedo in the water.
Closing fast, maybe 40 seconds.

274
00:20:32,773 --> 00:20:35,275
- Yes. Status on my torpedo?
- Torpedo ready, but...

275
00:20:35,443 --> 00:20:39,529
Thirty-second fuse. Match our speed
and bearing after breakaway.

276
00:20:39,739 --> 00:20:40,822
Fire.

277
00:20:42,450 --> 00:20:44,492
You heard him. Fire.

278
00:20:47,330 --> 00:20:48,496
[WHOOSHING]

279
00:20:52,835 --> 00:20:56,004
- Torpedo away.
- Hostile closing, 55 knots.

280
00:21:02,178 --> 00:21:06,181
You got us 20 degrees down bubble.
Ahead, full. Queeg, you're taking...

281
00:21:06,349 --> 00:21:09,017
Taking the boat to 729.8 meters.

282
00:21:09,185 --> 00:21:11,353
- Crush depth.
- The edge of crush depth.

283
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:13,188
The kraken won't be able to follow.

284
00:21:13,356 --> 00:21:16,024
Their sonar will reflect
off the thermocline layer.

285
00:21:16,192 --> 00:21:17,859
- We'll be...
- Invisible.

286
00:21:18,027 --> 00:21:20,820
- We're playing dead.
- Eight seconds to torpedo contact.

287
00:21:20,988 --> 00:21:24,157
- Approaching crush depth.
- If he's off by even a millimeter...

288
00:21:24,325 --> 00:21:28,036
- ...for even a fraction of a second...
- He won't be. This is what he does.

289
00:21:29,664 --> 00:21:32,415
Two detonations. Our torpedo and theirs.

290
00:21:32,583 --> 00:21:35,502
Eleven hundred meters to starboard,
120 on the Z.

291
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:39,589
And now we roll over,
stick out our tongue, hold our breath.

292
00:21:39,799 --> 00:21:41,800
[HULL CREAKING]

293
00:21:46,514 --> 00:21:50,684
- Skipper, we're at 729.8.
- I'm aware, chief. Thank you.

294
00:21:53,604 --> 00:21:56,231
729.8 and holding.

295
00:22:02,321 --> 00:22:04,572
You may return
to your duty stations now.

296
00:22:08,202 --> 00:22:10,245
You heard the captain, people.

297
00:22:10,621 --> 00:22:14,582
What, you never been 20 centimeters
from your maker before? Move.

298
00:22:18,587 --> 00:22:21,631
Skipper, when we're done
skating over our deaths...

299
00:22:21,841 --> 00:22:23,925
...I got a question.

300
00:22:25,594 --> 00:22:28,430
Why are we 300 miles off course?

301
00:22:46,449 --> 00:22:50,285
We were using it for research,
to find out what makes them...

302
00:22:50,453 --> 00:22:53,997
Don't, John. Just don't.

303
00:22:54,165 --> 00:22:56,624
Don't make excuses for her.
Don't cover for her.

304
00:22:57,626 --> 00:23:00,295
- I knew about the parts...
- I'm not talking about the parts.

305
00:23:02,631 --> 00:23:04,674
I'm talking about Riley.

306
00:23:10,639 --> 00:23:14,100
Well, there's nothing to talk about,
is there? Because Riley's dead.

307
00:23:15,019 --> 00:23:16,936
How do you think that happened?

308
00:23:17,104 --> 00:23:19,189
I don't know.

309
00:23:20,107 --> 00:23:21,649
I'm gonna figure it out, though.

310
00:23:22,526 --> 00:23:24,944
You know, John. We both know.

311
00:23:29,617 --> 00:23:31,034
No.

312
00:23:32,036 --> 00:23:33,495
Cameron didn't do it.

313
00:23:33,662 --> 00:23:35,955
How can you say that?

314
00:23:36,123 --> 00:23:37,832
How can you be sure?

315
00:23:39,293 --> 00:23:43,963
Because I'm sure, and I know her...

316
00:23:44,840 --> 00:23:46,716
...and she told me.

317
00:23:47,510 --> 00:23:49,344
She told you.

318
00:23:51,305 --> 00:23:55,183
Just like she told you she destroyed
every part we ever captured.

319
00:23:55,351 --> 00:23:58,686
Just like she tells us what she does
every night when we go to sleep.

320
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:03,149
When she comes back in the morning,
she's covered in cuts and bruises.

321
00:24:04,693 --> 00:24:07,487
Hey. Just like she told you
she loved you.

322
00:24:19,041 --> 00:24:21,751
You don't know anything.

323
00:24:33,389 --> 00:24:35,306
I'm thinking of an herb.

324
00:24:36,267 --> 00:24:37,892
- Tarragon?
- No.

325
00:24:38,060 --> 00:24:40,895
- We're wasting time.
- But it's working, his game.

326
00:24:41,063 --> 00:24:45,441
What is wrong with you?
Why are you not angry?

327
00:24:46,610 --> 00:24:49,779
Why should I be?
We have a way to get her back.

328
00:24:49,947 --> 00:24:53,908
Tell me where the child is.

329
00:24:55,911 --> 00:24:57,662
[SIGHS]

330
00:24:57,830 --> 00:25:02,083
Look, you asked me to teach him
ethics, morals and rules.

331
00:25:02,668 --> 00:25:04,919
What good is it
if he's not gonna follow them?

332
00:25:05,087 --> 00:25:09,048
He will, if we let him
learn the rules on his own.

333
00:25:15,472 --> 00:25:17,140
Oregano.

334
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:22,604
- Correct.
- See there? A lucky guess.

335
00:25:22,771 --> 00:25:26,274
- Lucky.
- Give us our clue.

336
00:25:26,442 --> 00:25:28,776
The sun is shining on Savannah.

337
00:25:30,487 --> 00:25:31,988
Security.

338
00:25:32,156 --> 00:25:35,867
Check near all windows.
Any place light is coming through.

339
00:25:37,703 --> 00:25:40,288
I'm thinking of an animal.

340
00:25:42,791 --> 00:25:45,460
- Antelope.
- No.

341
00:25:45,628 --> 00:25:47,170
- Lion.
- No.

342
00:25:47,338 --> 00:25:48,796
- Horse.
- No.

343
00:25:48,964 --> 00:25:50,798
- Bird.
- Correct.

344
00:25:50,966 --> 00:25:54,010
- Give us our clue.
- The answer is the clue.

345
00:25:55,638 --> 00:25:57,639
What? What does that mean?

346
00:25:57,806 --> 00:26:01,142
Just what he said. "Bird" is our clue.

347
00:26:05,981 --> 00:26:13,863
Bird.

348
00:26:21,997 --> 00:26:23,039
I know where she is.

349
00:26:28,003 --> 00:26:30,880
Security, meet us
at the elevators.

350
00:26:46,855 --> 00:26:48,523
Savannah, are you okay?

351
00:26:50,651 --> 00:26:51,859
Mm-hm.

352
00:26:53,279 --> 00:26:55,530
Come here, come here.

353
00:26:58,534 --> 00:27:00,702
Here, go to your mother.

354
00:27:01,203 --> 00:27:04,038
You found me, Mommy.

355
00:27:04,206 --> 00:27:07,875
Yes, darling, I did.

356
00:27:12,798 --> 00:27:14,299
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

357
00:27:17,553 --> 00:27:21,264
Hey, Aaron. John.

358
00:27:21,432 --> 00:27:22,890
I remember.

359
00:27:24,476 --> 00:27:28,479
- Is Riley around?
- No. She didn't come home last night.

360
00:27:29,231 --> 00:27:30,982
Riley didn't come home?

361
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:36,070
Thanks.

362
00:27:36,238 --> 00:27:40,616
Foster kids. That's the way it is
with them sometimes.

363
00:27:40,784 --> 00:27:45,788
They drift into your life,
and then they drift back out again.

364
00:27:46,832 --> 00:27:49,083
Not always according to plan.

365
00:27:51,920 --> 00:27:53,463
She's a tough one too.

366
00:27:55,132 --> 00:27:59,719
Good heart, as I'm sure you know,
but tough to know.

367
00:28:04,224 --> 00:28:07,101
Well, uh, I really needed to talk to her.

368
00:28:07,269 --> 00:28:10,938
I don't know if you can maybe
just take a message for me, or...?

369
00:28:11,106 --> 00:28:12,106
[PHONE RINGING]

370
00:28:12,274 --> 00:28:14,194
- See, the last time we spoke...
- Hang on a sec.

371
00:28:15,944 --> 00:28:17,612
Hello?

372
00:28:19,239 --> 00:28:24,786
Riley. God, Riley, are you all right?
Where are you?

373
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:29,290
[IN RILEY'S VOICE] Everything's fine.
I'm in Riverside. It's a long story.

374
00:28:29,458 --> 00:28:31,626
- Everything's fine.
- We've been worried sick.

375
00:28:31,794 --> 00:28:36,130
- We were about to call the police.
- Please don't do that. Everything's fine.

376
00:28:36,298 --> 00:28:41,677
- John too. He's here.
- John? Really? Can I talk to him?

377
00:28:44,807 --> 00:28:46,474
Me?

378
00:28:48,268 --> 00:28:49,977
Riley?

379
00:28:50,145 --> 00:28:53,022
You're in Riverside. Okay.

380
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:58,319
Well, listen, we'll talk when I see you.

381
00:28:58,987 --> 00:29:00,780
I thought you'd wanna hear my voice.

382
00:29:02,658 --> 00:29:05,660
You know you're really
freaking everybody out, right?

383
00:29:06,995 --> 00:29:08,996
Am I freaking you out now?

384
00:29:09,790 --> 00:29:11,416
Yes...

385
00:29:13,502 --> 00:29:16,379
- ...so let's talk later.
- I'm sorry.

386
00:29:16,588 --> 00:29:20,716
It's just... I've been thinking
about my parents a lot...

387
00:29:20,884 --> 00:29:23,386
...and there are things
I can't get out of my head...

388
00:29:23,554 --> 00:29:27,014
...and I just thought if I came out
and saw where we used to live...

389
00:29:27,808 --> 00:29:31,060
I know. Stupid, right?

390
00:29:31,228 --> 00:29:35,398
Okay, well, we'll talk about all this
in person, yeah? When you get back.

391
00:29:39,736 --> 00:29:43,448
- We're hanging up now. Ha-ha.
- John?

392
00:29:43,615 --> 00:29:45,199
Yeah, sure. That would be great.

393
00:29:46,243 --> 00:29:49,120
- John?
- Yeah?

394
00:29:50,873 --> 00:29:52,039
I love you.

395
00:29:56,253 --> 00:29:58,254
Okay, bye.

396
00:30:05,053 --> 00:30:07,365
What was that about?
[IN NORMAL VOICE] What was what about?

397
00:30:07,389 --> 00:30:08,556
What happened just now.

398
00:30:09,558 --> 00:30:10,600
It was the plan.

399
00:30:11,226 --> 00:30:14,228
No, the plan
was to call the foster parents.

400
00:30:14,396 --> 00:30:17,064
The plan was to let him hear her voice.

401
00:30:18,734 --> 00:30:19,775
That's what I did.

402
00:30:21,361 --> 00:30:23,070
That's not all you did.

403
00:30:23,572 --> 00:30:25,406
What you did was not the plan.

404
00:30:25,991 --> 00:30:28,826
The plan was to make him think
she's still alive...

405
00:30:28,994 --> 00:30:31,621
...so he wouldn't go to the police.

406
00:30:31,788 --> 00:30:36,250
You became part of that plan.
Your reaction made it more authentic.

407
00:30:36,418 --> 00:30:38,794
Don't you think
it was more authentic that way?

408
00:30:44,801 --> 00:30:46,260
Where are we going now?

409
00:30:46,887 --> 00:30:49,347
We're not going anywhere.

410
00:30:49,515 --> 00:30:52,016
I'm going somewhere...

411
00:30:52,184 --> 00:30:53,851
...and I'm gonna go alone.

412
00:30:54,019 --> 00:30:56,604
- You shouldn't be alone.
- Yes, I should.

413
00:31:07,449 --> 00:31:09,825
Did you have fun playing the game,
Mr. Ellison?

414
00:31:09,993 --> 00:31:14,121
- No, John Henry, I did not.
- Why not?

415
00:31:14,289 --> 00:31:16,916
Because what you did made me very,
very angry.

416
00:31:17,084 --> 00:31:20,169
- I don't understand.
- You kept a secret.

417
00:31:21,255 --> 00:31:22,755
Is it wrong to keep a secret?

418
00:31:22,965 --> 00:31:26,133
The secret you kept
could've harmed Savannah.

419
00:31:26,343 --> 00:31:28,469
What if we couldn't have found her?

420
00:31:28,637 --> 00:31:31,097
What if she'd fallen from the roof
and died?

421
00:31:33,475 --> 00:31:38,145
Then she wouldn't be alive anymore,
and her life is important.

422
00:31:38,897 --> 00:31:40,314
Human life is sacred.

423
00:31:40,482 --> 00:31:43,818
If she had died, it would be your fault.

424
00:31:45,946 --> 00:31:47,154
My fault?

425
00:31:47,364 --> 00:31:49,991
Because you were the only one
who knew where she was...

426
00:31:50,784 --> 00:31:52,994
...and you made a choice not to tell.

427
00:31:54,079 --> 00:31:55,663
It was the wrong choice.

428
00:32:06,800 --> 00:32:08,384
Derek?

429
00:32:10,512 --> 00:32:12,597
I'm thinking about Riley.

430
00:32:14,391 --> 00:32:15,766
What the cyborg did to her.

431
00:32:17,519 --> 00:32:18,811
It's a terrible thing.

432
00:32:19,771 --> 00:32:21,355
But...

433
00:32:22,107 --> 00:32:25,610
...if John realizes what the metal is...

434
00:32:25,777 --> 00:32:27,945
...what it really does...

435
00:32:29,448 --> 00:32:31,157
...maybe some good can come of it.

436
00:32:33,535 --> 00:32:35,870
Maybe you can help him see that.

437
00:32:36,496 --> 00:32:38,039
Good?

438
00:32:40,917 --> 00:32:43,502
An innocent kid is dead.

439
00:32:45,964 --> 00:32:51,969
That metal bitch murdered her in
cold blood. No good comes out of that.

440
00:32:53,472 --> 00:32:55,348
None. Not ever.

441
00:32:58,894 --> 00:33:00,978
You're a good man.

442
00:33:05,942 --> 00:33:07,485
Oh, yeah?

443
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:14,909
Don't let anyone tell you different.

444
00:33:27,673 --> 00:33:30,424
[SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

445
00:33:32,386 --> 00:33:33,719
[SIGHS]

446
00:33:38,767 --> 00:33:42,520
We've been bearing 30 degrees
off-course for four hours...

447
00:33:42,688 --> 00:33:45,606
...into a major Skynet zone.
What's going on?

448
00:33:45,774 --> 00:33:47,608
Our new mission required it.

449
00:33:48,402 --> 00:33:50,736
What mission? Where are we headed?

450
00:33:50,904 --> 00:33:54,740
A deep-water oil platform
near the Indonesian archipelago.

451
00:33:54,908 --> 00:33:59,036
Lieutenant Dietz and his team
will board the rig and retrieve a package.

452
00:33:59,204 --> 00:34:01,622
We will deliver this package
to Serrano Point.

453
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:05,251
We have important cargo to take to Perth.
Components, vaccines...

454
00:34:05,419 --> 00:34:07,503
Our orders come from John Connor.

455
00:34:10,549 --> 00:34:14,218
These orders from John Connor,
do they say what we're after?

456
00:34:14,386 --> 00:34:15,636
What it is?

457
00:34:15,804 --> 00:34:18,139
Yes. They say what the package is.

458
00:34:19,766 --> 00:34:20,808
Right.

459
00:34:24,980 --> 00:34:28,232
Please inform the crew. Thank you.

460
00:34:35,991 --> 00:34:37,658
[SIGHS]

461
00:34:37,826 --> 00:34:40,661
JESSE: Just stay sharp. You'll be fine.
- Oh, I know I'll be fine.

462
00:34:40,829 --> 00:34:41,829
[GUN COCKS]

463
00:34:41,997 --> 00:34:43,831
- I got this.
- I'm serious, Dietz.

464
00:34:45,041 --> 00:34:48,461
- I'm always serious about being fine.
- You do me one favor.

465
00:34:49,671 --> 00:34:53,799
You see anything you don't like,
you think before you pull that trigger.

466
00:34:54,760 --> 00:34:57,178
I've been seeing things I don't like
since J-Day.

467
00:34:57,345 --> 00:35:00,639
You don't get to be my age
without thinking first.

468
00:35:02,809 --> 00:35:06,854
I swear, Mom. We'll hold hands
before we cross the street.

469
00:35:10,650 --> 00:35:15,321
ASDS has cut engines, commander.
I think we're clear for comms.

470
00:35:15,489 --> 00:35:17,823
ASDS, this is Carter, over.

471
00:35:17,991 --> 00:35:21,202
DIETZ: Hey, Mom. I'll say this much
about a deep-sea oil rig:

472
00:35:21,369 --> 00:35:24,163
Second-worst thing I've ever smelled.
Dark as night out hete.

473
00:35:24,331 --> 00:35:26,040
We're gonna keep this channel open.

474
00:35:26,208 --> 00:35:29,001
Maintain radio silence
till you've got the package.

475
00:35:29,169 --> 00:35:30,836
Planning on it.

476
00:35:31,880 --> 00:35:33,881
[RAIN PATTERING]

477
00:35:34,049 --> 00:35:36,050
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

478
00:37:31,082 --> 00:37:35,002
Connor sent me. John Connor.

479
00:37:36,504 --> 00:37:38,297
I've come for that.

480
00:37:39,007 --> 00:37:40,215
That's for him.

481
00:37:42,135 --> 00:37:43,469
I'm just here to pick it up.

482
00:38:18,254 --> 00:38:20,255
[METAL CLANKING]

483
00:38:25,804 --> 00:38:27,805
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

484
00:38:39,609 --> 00:38:43,779
I had planned on waiting for you
with Derek's sniper rifle.

485
00:38:43,989 --> 00:38:49,702
Pulled the trigger, solved about
50 percent of my problems. One shot.

486
00:38:53,081 --> 00:38:55,416
Do you know how bad I'd have felt?

487
00:38:56,001 --> 00:38:59,253
- Very bad?
- Not bad at all.

488
00:39:00,755 --> 00:39:03,757
But I know someone
who'd have felt bad.

489
00:39:04,551 --> 00:39:07,052
Someone who would never forgive me
if I'd done that.

490
00:39:09,389 --> 00:39:11,640
I don't know what to do with you.

491
00:39:13,018 --> 00:39:16,020
You know what the stakes are.
You know why we're here.

492
00:39:17,397 --> 00:39:19,565
You know what this means.

493
00:39:20,608 --> 00:39:23,777
And yet here I stand,
burning what's left of an endoskeleton...

494
00:39:23,945 --> 00:39:26,822
- ...I thought we'd burned months ago.
- I needed spare parts.

495
00:39:27,032 --> 00:39:30,325
I don't care what you need,
because this is not about you.

496
00:39:30,535 --> 00:39:34,955
No, it's not about me. It's about John.

497
00:39:38,460 --> 00:39:40,502
You're concerned for his safety.

498
00:39:40,670 --> 00:39:43,172
- You bet I am.
- From Skynet.

499
00:39:43,923 --> 00:39:46,633
- From me.
- Maybe.

500
00:39:47,677 --> 00:39:49,636
Maybe especially you.

501
00:39:50,638 --> 00:39:55,142
We're all a threat.
We're all a threat to John.

502
00:39:57,312 --> 00:40:01,648
He worries about us.
That makes him vulnerable.

503
00:40:03,109 --> 00:40:04,651
He cares.

504
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:08,113
I am not John's problem.

505
00:40:08,948 --> 00:40:13,285
John is John's problem.
Humans are the problem.

506
00:40:14,829 --> 00:40:17,831
There's only one way for him to be safe.

507
00:40:17,999 --> 00:40:19,500
That's to be alone.

508
00:40:20,877 --> 00:40:23,337
What kind of life is that?

509
00:40:23,588 --> 00:40:27,883
John's life, someday.

510
00:42:25,251 --> 00:42:27,252
I'm sorry.

